name: Notanengineerbut
review: This curler, along with MANY others available now have a DESIGN FLAW that keeps them from curling lashes properly.  The black rubber insert is "humped" or convex.  When the metal part comes down on it when you squeeze the curler, it forces the lashes into an un-natural downward angle around the "hump".  Duh!  Pretty obvious there was no product testing and no engineering knowledge and now they are everywhere.  For an eyelash curler to work properly, the black rubber insert needs to be either flat or concave to force the lashes down and then up as the curler is squeezed.  Really simple here - why was this changed?  Dumb Dumb Dumb.  Eyelash curlers used to work fine.

I used this curler for a while, but always found that I had to push and re-curl several times in order for my lashes to curl up at all. I have long lashes, and it just took quite a bit of effort to get my lashes looking nice and perky.

It's also not the best quality. My first one broke pretty easily (probably because I had to squeeze the living daylights out of it to get it to curl). I thought maybe I bought a flawed one the first time, but the second one I bought also broke!

review: This curls my lashes, but doesn't feel like it's tugging on my lashes or my eyelids when I use it. I like it.

name: Alicia
review:
I never bothered to use an eyelash curler before, so thought I'd pick one up.
After seeing how expensive bigger brands are (which is pretty ridiculous,btw;can't imagine better ones even cost too much too make), I picked this one up.
It's ok. It gets the job done, but not without pressing down pretty hard and pushing the curler handle upwards a little.
It is also very large for my eyes,yet with my face shape (prominent cheeks) and the shape of the curler, it puts the curler too far from my lashes, making it a bit more problematic. It's very hard to angle correctly, and I still have to go back in a second time to get the remaining lashes because it's just so far away from my lids that it can't reach all the lashes at once. Very weird.
I like the way my lashes look after I get the curl, but I wouldn't use this if I were trying to conserve time.
I wouldn't purchase again. Guess I'll try a $20 one and cross my fingers that it's better.

name: Tj
review: Didn't work for me at all

name: Beauty Queen
review: Curler doesn't open as wide as others, making it a little more difficult.

name: MIlk Cow
review: i like this since it is easy to use. but, the curl does not last very long and i have to constantly curl my lashes again and again. good product though!

name: Lethe
review:
When I got this out of the packaging, I could see ... something wasn't right. The thing is warped - one rod is longer than the other so it doesn't line up properly.

It feels and sounds flimsy (I had another one in the past, but couldn't find it, so I nabbed this one - bad idea!), and as another reviewer mentioned, I have fears of clamping my flesh with it. It's shaped such that I'm not able to get a decent grip on my lashes, either - it's like the curve is too broad for my eye, so I'm only able to curl half the lashes on one eye at a time.

Since I'd rather not lose my eyelid, I'm looking for a replacement. Maybe one that can get all my lashes without trying to pop my eye out.
